<!DOCTYPE article PUBLIC "-//OASIS//DTD DocBook V3.1//EN" [
]>

<article>
  <artheader>
    <title>
      Requirements for Hermes: The Home Exercise Program
    </title>
    <author>
      <firstname>Chuck</firstname>
      <surname>Hardin</surname>
    </author>
  </artheader>

  <sect1>
    <title>Abstract</title>
    <para>
      Hermes is an application which guides a user through exercise
      routines and logs her progress.  It uses audio cues during a
      routine as the primary means of pacing movements.  This document
      specifies the requirements for such a system.
    </para>
      
  </sect1>

  <sect1>
    <title>Background</title>
    <para>
      I've
      used <ulink url='https://www.medbridgego.com/access_token'>MedBridge
      GO</ulink> to guide my home exercise program, to share my
      exercise progress with my physical therapist, and later to
      record that progress when my time with her was over.  It's not a
      bad app, but it has a number of shortcomings for my use, and I
      have not seen a replacement that will fill those lacunae.</para>
    <sect2>
      <title>Benefits of MedBridge GO</title>
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It presents a routine as a collection of exercises.  An
	    exercise has a count of sets, a count of reps per set, and
	    a sequence of moves per rep with specified timing.  This
	    is fairly easy to grasp in concept and suggests a
	    straightforward data representation.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It provides the user with a simple visual and audio guide
	    to perform an exercise routine.  She is guided through
	    every motion.  Supplementary hints about how best to
	    perform each exercise are available by hitting an
	    information icon.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It gives the user an easy way to save their progress after
	    completing a routine.  The typical use case requires only
	    a few button presses and the thing is done.</para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Drawbacks of MedBridge GO</title>
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It doesn't allow the user to alter her regimen
	    autonomously.  Only her therapist can do that.  As I have
	    progressed, I find I want to add sets to an exercise or
	    new exercises to a routine.  MedBridge GO does not support
	    that.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It doesn't make allowance for noting changes in the
	    intensity of an exercise other than rep count or elapsed
	    time.  For example, there is no way to record changes in
	    resistance.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    Its cues are mostly visual, in the form of videos.  There
	    are few audio indications of progress, mostly a tone at
	    the beginning of the last three reps of an exercise.  This
	    requires me to look at a screen during exercises, which I
	    find inconvenient.  At the least, I want audio cues at
	    critical parts of an exercise and a cue for each
	    rep.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It requires an internet connection to function and uses
	    that connection to send exercise information to its
	    servers. I may not want to share that with others.  I may
	    in future want to add that capability, but I do not want
	    it by default.  I prefer my privacy.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    It allows only a limited abioity to keep track of changes
	    to the user's regimen over time.  A user can enter such
	    chanmges when recording a given exercise session, but I
	    cannot see them in the interface.  Also, as previously
	    stated, those user-recoreded changes do not persist for
	    future routines, since only the therapist can make
	    permanent changes to a routine.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    MedBridge GO does not provide its source code.  I want to
	    be able to change the system's behavior, possibly in ways
	    I do not currently anticipate.  It is very likely that I
	    will share this code publicly under an open source
	    license, possibly the GPL.</para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>

  <sect1>
    <title>Phased requirements</title>
    <sect2>
      <title>Storing routines and generating audio output</title>
      <sect3>
	<title>Storing routine data</title>
	<orderedlist>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      The app must support multiple users, each with their own
	      routine data.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A user can have named routines.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A routine may have exercises.</para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      An exercise will have a count of sets, a count of reps
	      per set, and a sequence of moves.  It may have a
	      supplemental description </para>
	  </listitem>
	  <listitem>
	    <para>
	      A move will have a specified duration and may have .</para>
	  </listitem>
	</orderedlist>
      </sect3>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Storing records of progress via a web interface</title>
      <para></para>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Editing routines via a web interface </title>
      <para></para>
    </sect2>
    <sect2>
      <title>Dynamic generation of audio output</title>
      <para></para>
    </sect2>
  </sect1>
  
 </article>
